# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cell-wall
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cell-wall/1-3-beta-glucan-synthase] The biosynthesis of disaccharides, oligosaccharides, and polysaccharides involves the action of hundreds of different glycosyltransferases.
[src:cell-wall/1-3-beta-glucan-synthase] These enzymes catalyse the transfer of sugar moieties from activated donor molecules to specific acceptor molecules, forming glycosidic bonds.
[src:cell-wall/1-3-beta-glucan-synthase] The family consists of various 1,3-beta-glucan synthase components including Gls1, Gls2, and Gls3 from yeast.
[src:cell-wall/1-3-beta-glucan-synthase] 1,3-Beta-glucan synthase (EC 2.4.1.34.) also known as callose synthase catalyses the formation of a beta-1,3-glucan polymer that is a major component of the fungal cell wall.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The **ABC model of flower development** is a scientific model of the process by which flowering plants produce a pattern of gene expression in meristems that leads to the appearance of an organ oriented towards sexual reproduction, a flower.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The latter phase has been modelled using the **ABC model**, which aims to describe the biological basis of the process from the perspective of molecular and developmental genetics.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] An external stimulus is required in order to trigger the differentiation of the meristem into a flower meristem.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This stimulus will activate mitotic cell division in the apical meristem, particularly on its sides where new primordia are formed.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This same stimulus will also cause the meristem to follow a developmental pattern that will lead to the growth of floral meristems as opposed to vegetative meristems.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The main difference between these two types of meristem, apart from the obvious disparity between the objective organ, is the verticillate (or whorled) phyllotaxis, that is, the absence of stem elongation among the successive whorls or verticils of the primordium.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] These verticils follow an acropetal development, giving rise to sepals, petals, stamens and carpels.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Another difference from vegetative axillary meristems is that the floral meristem is "determined", which means that, once differentiated, its cells will no longer divide.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The identity of the organs present in the four floral verticils is a consequence of the interaction of at least three types of gene products, each with distinct functions.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] According to the ABC model, functions A and C are required in order to determine the identity of the verticils of the perianth and the reproductive verticils, respectively.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] These functions are exclusive and the absence of one of them means that the other will determine the identity of all the floral verticils.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B function allows the differentiation of petals from sepals in the secondary verticil, as well as the differentiation of the stamen from the carpel on the tertiary verticil.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Goethe's **foliar theory** was formulated in the 18th century and it suggests that the constituent parts of a flower are structurally modified leaves, which are functionally specialized for reproduction or protection.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The transition from the vegetative phase to a reproductive phase involves a dramatic change in the plant's vital cycle, perhaps the most important one, as the process must be carried out correctly in order to guarantee that the plant produces descendants.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This transition is characterised by the induction and development of the meristem of the inflorescence, which will produce a collection of flowers or one flower.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This morphogenetic change contains both endogenous and exogenous elements: For example, in order for the change to be initiated the plant must have a certain number of leaves and contain a certain level of total biomass.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Certain environmental conditions are also required such as a characteristic photoperiod.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Plant hormones play an important part in the process, with the gibberellins having a particularly important role.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are many signals that regulate the molecular biology of the process.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The following three genes in *Arabidopsis thaliana* possess both common and independent functions in floral transition: *FLOWERING LOCUS T* (*FT*), *LEAFY* (*LFY*), *SUPPRESSOR OF OVEREXPRESSION OF CONSTANS1* (*SOC1*, also called *AGAMOUS-LIKE20*).
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] *SOC1* is a MADS-box-type gene, which integrates responses to photoperiod, vernalization and gibberellins.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The meristem can be defined as the tissue or group of plant tissues that contain undifferentiated stem cells, which are capable of producing any type of cell tissue.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Their maintenance and development, both in the vegetative meristem or the meristem of the inflorescence is controlled by genetic cell fate determination mechanisms.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that a number of genes will directly regulate, for example, the maintenance of the stem cell's characteristics (gene *WUSCHEL* or *WUS*), and others will act via negative feedback mechanisms in order to inhibit a characteristic (gene *CLAVATA* or *CLV*).
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this way both mechanisms give rise to a feedback loop, which along with other elements lend a great deal of robustness to the system.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Along with the *WUS* gene the *SHOOTMERISTEMLESS* (*STM*) gene also represses the differentiation of the meristematic dome.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This gene acts by inhibiting the possible differentiation of the stem cells but still allows cell division in the daughter cells, which, had they been allowed to differentiate, would have given rise to distinct organs.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] A flower's anatomy, as defined by the presence of a series of organs (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels) positioned according to a given pattern, facilitate sexual reproduction in flowering plants.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model of flower development was first formulated by George Haughn and Chris Somerville in 1988.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was first used as a model to describe the collection of genetic mechanisms that establish floral organ identity in the Rosids, as exemplified by *Arabidopsis thaliana*, and the Asterids, as demonstrated by *Antirrhinum majus*.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both species have four verticils (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels), which are defined by the differential expression of a number of homeotic genes present in each verticil.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that the sepals are solely characterized by the expression of A genes, while the petals are characterized by the co-expression of A and B genes.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B and C genes establish the identity of the stamens and the carpels only require C genes to be active.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Type A and C genes are reciprocally antagonistic.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The fact that these homeotic genes determine an organ's identity becomes evident when a gene that represents a particular function, for example the A gene, is not expressed.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* this loss results in a flower which is composed of one verticil of carpels, another containing stamens and another of carpels.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This method for studying gene function uses reverse genetics techniques to produce transgenic plants that contain a mechanism for gene silencing through RNA interference.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In other studies, using forward genetics techniques such as genetic mapping, it is the analysis of the phenotypes of flowers with structural anomalies that leads to the cloning of the gene of interest.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The flowers may possess a non-functional or over expressed allele for the gene being studied.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The existence of two supplementary functions, D and E, have also been proposed in addition to the A, B and C functions already discussed.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function D specifies the identity of the ovule, as a separate reproductive function from the development of the carpels, which occurs after their determination.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function E relates to a physiological requirement that is a characteristic of all floral verticils, although, it was initially described as necessary for the development of the three innermost verticils (Function E *sensu stricto*).
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, its broader definition (*sensu lato*) suggests that it is required in the four verticils.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The gene products of genes with D and E functions are also MADS-box genes.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The methodology for studying flower development involves two steps.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Firstly, the identification of the exact genes required for determining the identity of the floral meristem.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* these include APETALA1 (*AP1*) and LEAFY (*LFY*).
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Secondly, genetic analysis is carried out on the aberrant phenotypes for the relative characteristics of the flowers, which allows the characterization of the homeotic genes implicated in the process.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are a great many mutations that affect floral morphology, although the analysis of these mutants is a recent development.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Supporting evidence for the existence of these mutations comes from the fact that a large number affect the identity of floral organs.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] For example, some organs develop in a location where others should develop.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is called homeotic mutation, which is analogous to HOX gene mutations found in *Drosophila*.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* and *Antirrhinum*, the two taxa on which models are based, these mutations always affect adjacent verticils.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Cloning studies have been carried out on DNA in the genes associated with the affected homeotic functions in the mutants discussed above.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] These studies used serial analysis of gene expression throughout floral development to show patterns of tissue expression, which, in general, correspond with the predictions of the ABC model.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The nature of these genes corresponds to that of transcription factors, which, as expected, have analogous structures to a group of factors contained in yeasts and animal cells.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This group is called MADS, which is an acronym for the different factors contained in the group.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] These MADS factors have been detected in all the vegetable species studied, although the involvement of other elements involved in the regulation of gene expression cannot be discounted.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, function A is mainly represented by two genes *APETALA1* (*AP1)* and *APETALA2* (*AP2*) *AP1* is a MADS-box type gene, while *AP2* belongs to the family of genes that contains AP2, which it gives its name to and which consists of transcription factors that are only found in plants.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] AP2 has also been shown to complex with the co-repressor TOPLESS (TPL) in developing floral buds to repress the C-class gene *AGAMOUS* (*AG*).
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] *AP2* not only functions in the first two verticils, but also in the remaining two, in developing ovules and even in leaves.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] It is also likely that post-transcriptional regulation exists, which controls its A function, or even that it has other purposes in the determination of organ identity independent of that mentioned here.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Antirrhinum*, the orthologous gene to *AP1* is *SQUAMOSA* (*SQUA*), which also has a particular impact on the floral meristem.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs for *AP2* are *LIPLESS1* (*LIP1*) and *LIPLESS2* (*LIP2*), which have a redundant function and are of special interest in the development of sepals, petals and ovules.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] A total of three genes have been isolated from *Petunia hybrida* that are similar to *AP2*: *P. hybrida APETALA2A* (*PhAP2A*), *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] *PhAP2A* is, to a large degree, homologous with the *AP2* gene of *Arabidopsis*, both in its sequence and in its expression pattern, which suggests that the two genes are orthologs.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The proteins *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*, on the other hand, are slightly different, even though they belong to the family of transcription factors that are similar to *AP2*.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition they are expressed in different ways, although they are very similar in comparison with *PhAP2A*.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In fact, the mutants for these genes do not show the usual phenotype, that of the null alleles of A genes.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* the type-B function mainly arises from two genes, *APETALA3* (*AP3*) and *PISTILLATA* (*PI*), both of which are MADS-box genes.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] A mutation of either of these genes causes the homeotic conversion of petals into sepals and of stamens into carpels.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This also occurs in its orthologs in *A. majus*, which are DEFICIENS (*DEF*) and *GLOBOSA* (*GLO*) respectively.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] For both species the active form of binding with DNA is that derived from the heterodimer: AP3 and PI, or DEF and GLO, dimerize.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is the form in which they are able to function.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *GLO*/*PI* lines that have been duplicated in *Petunia* contain *P. hybrida GLOBOSA1* (*PhGLO1*, also called *FBP1*) and also *PhGLO2* (also called *PMADS2* or *FBP3*).
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] For the functional elements equivalent to *AP3*/*DEF* in *Petunia* there is both a gene that possesses a relatively similar sequence, called *PhDEF* and there is also an atypical B function gene called PhTM6.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic studies have placed the first three within the «euAP3» lineage, while PhTM6 belongs to that of «paleoAP3».
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] As discussed above, the floral organs of eudicotyledonous angiosperms are arranged in 4 different verticils, containing the sepals, petals, stamen and carpels.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model states that the identity of these organs is determined by the homeotic genes A, A+B, B+C and C, respectively.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In contrast with the sepal and petal verticils of the eudicots, the perigone of many plants of the family Liliaceae have two nearly identical external petaloid verticils (the tepals).
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In order to explain the floral morphology of the Liliaceae, van Tunen *et al.* proposed a modified ABC model in 1993.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This model suggests that class B genes are not only expressed in verticils 2 and 3, but also in 1.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] It therefore follows that the organs of verticils 1 and 2 express class A and B genes and this is how they have a petaloid structure.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] This theoretical model has been experimentally proven through the cloning and characterization of homologs of the *Antirrhinum* genes *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* in a Liliaceae, the tulip *Tulipa gesneriana*.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are expressed in verticils 1,2 and 3.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* have also been isolated and characterized in *Agapanthus praecox* ssp.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] *orientalis* (Agapanthaceae), which is phylogenetically distant from the model organisms.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this study the genes were called *ApGLO* and *ApDEF*, respectively.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both contain open reading frames that code for proteins with 210 to 214 amino acids.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic analysis of these sequences indicated that they belong to B gene family of the monocotyledons.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In situ hybridization studies revealed that both sequences are expressed in verticil 1 as well as in 2 and 3.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] When taken together, these observations show that the floral development mechanism of *Agapanthus* also follows the modified ABC model.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, the C function is derived from one MADS-box type gene called *AGAMOUS* (*AG*), which intervenes both in the establishment of stamen and carpel identity as well as in the determination of the floral meristem.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Therefore, the *AG* mutants are devoid of androecium and gynoecium and they have petals and sepals in their place.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition, the growth in the centre of the flower is undifferentiated, therefore the petals and sepals grow in repetitive verticils.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *PLENA* (*PLE*) gene is present in *A. majus*, in place of the *AG* gene, although it is not an ortholog.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, the *FARINELLI* (*FAR*) gene is an ortholog, which is specific to the development of the anthers and the maturation of pollen.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Petunia*, *Antirrhinum* and in maize the C function is controlled by a number of genes that act in the same manner.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The genes that are closer homologs of *AG* in *Petunia* are *pMADS3* and *floral-binding protein 6* (*FBP6*).
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The D function genes were discovered in 1995.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are MADS-box proteins and they have a function that is distinct from those previously described, although they have a certain homology with C function genes.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are called *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN7* (*FBP7*) and *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN1L* (*FBP1l*).
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was found that, in *Petunia*, they are involved in the development of the ovule.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] Equivalent genes were later found in *Arabidopsis*, where they are also involved in controlling the development of carpels and the ovule and even with structures related to seed dispersal.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The appearance of interesting phenotypes in RNA interference studies in *Petunia* and tomato led, in 1994, to the definition of a new type of function in the floral development model.
[src:cell-wall/abc-model-of-flower-development] The E function was initially thought to be only involved in the development of the three innermost verticils, however, subsequent work found that its expression was required in all the floral verticils.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] In ecology, **abiotic components** or **abiotic factors** are non-living chemical and physical parts of the environment that affect living organisms and the functioning of ecosystems.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] Abiotic factors and the phenomena associated with them underpin biology as a whole.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] They affect a wide range of species, across all forms of environmental conditions, such as marine or terrestrial animals.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] Humans can make or change abiotic factors in a species' environment.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] For instance, fertilizers can affect a snail's habitat, or the greenhouse gases which humans utilize can change marine pH levels.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] Abiotic components include physical conditions and non-living resources that affect living organisms in terms of growth, maintenance, and reproduction.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] Resources are distinguished as substances or objects in the environment required by one organism and consumed or otherwise made unavailable for use by other organisms.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] Component degradation of a substance occurs by chemical or physical processes, e.g. hydrolysis.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] All non-living components of an ecosystem, such as atmospheric conditions and water resources, are called abiotic components.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] In biology, abiotic factors can include water, light, radiation, temperature, humidity, atmosphere, acidity, salinity, precipitation, altitude, minerals, tides, rain, dissolved oxygen nutrients, and soil.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] The macroscopic climate often influences each of the above.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] Pressure and sound waves may also be considered in the context of marine or sub-terrestrial environments.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] Abiotic factors in ocean environments also include aerial exposure, substrate, water clarity, solar energy and tides.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] Consider the differences in the mechanics of C3, C4, and CAM plants in regulating the influx of carbon dioxide to the Calvin-Benson Cycle in relation to their abiotic stressors.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] C3 plants have no mechanisms to manage photorespiration, whereas C4 and CAM plants utilize a separate PEP carboxylase enzyme to prevent photorespiration, thus increasing the yield of photosynthesis processes in certain high energy environments.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] Many Archea require very high temperatures, pressures, or unusual concentrations of chemical substances such as sulfur; this is due to their specialization into extreme conditions.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] In addition, fungi have also evolved to survive at the temperature, the humidity, and stability of their environment.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] For example, there is a significant difference in access to both water and humidity between temperate rain forests and deserts.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] This difference in water availability causes a diversity in the organisms that survive in these areas.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] These differences in abiotic components alter the species present by creating boundaries of what species can survive within the environment and influencing competition between two species.
[src:cell-wall/abiotic-factor] Abiotic factors such as salinity can give one species a competitive advantage over another, creating pressures that lead to speciation and alteration of a species to and from generalist and specialist competitors.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] The **limiting reagent** (or **limiting reactant** or **limiting agent**) in a chemical reaction is a reactant that is totally consumed when the chemical reaction is completed.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] The amount of product formed is limited by this reagent, since the reaction cannot continue without it.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] If one or more other reagents are present in excess of the quantities required to react with the limiting reagent, they are described as *excess reagents* or *excess reactants* (sometimes abbreviated as "xs") or to be in *abundance*.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] The limiting reagent must be identified in order to calculate the percentage yield of a reaction since the theoretical yield is defined as the amount of product obtained when the limiting reagent reacts completely.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] Given the balanced chemical equation, which describes the reaction, there are several equivalent ways to identify the limiting reagent and evaluate the excess quantities of other reagents.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] This method is most useful when there are only two reactants.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] One reactant (A) is chosen, and the balanced chemical equation is used to determine the amount of the other reactant (B) necessary to react with A.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] If the amount of B actually present exceeds the amount required, then B is in excess and A is the limiting reagent.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] If the amount of B present is less than required, then B is the limiting reagent.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] The amount of oxygen required for other quantities of benzene can be calculated using cross-multiplication (the rule of three).
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] If in fact 18 mol O2 are present, there will be an excess of (18 - 11.25) = 6.75 mol of unreacted oxygen when all the benzene is consumed.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] Since the actual ratio is larger than required, O2 is the reagent in excess, which confirms that benzene is the limiting reagent.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] In this method the chemical equation is used to calculate the amount of one product which can be formed from each reactant in the amount present.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] The limiting reactant is the one which can form the smallest amount of the product considered.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] This method can be extended to any number of reactants more easily than the first method.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] Since the reactant amounts are given in grams, they must be first converted into moles for comparison with the chemical equation, in order to determine how many moles of Fe can be produced from either reactant.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] There is enough Al to produce 0.297 mol Fe, but only enough Fe2O3 to produce 0.250 mol Fe.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] This means that the amount of Fe actually produced is limited by the Fe2O3 present, which is therefore the limiting reagent.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] This value is the extent of reaction required to deplete each reagent to zero.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] The reagent that decreases to zero moles with the lowest extent of reaction is the limiting reagent.
[src:cell-wall/abundance-chemistry] The extent value can be multiplied by the stoichiometric coefficients of the other reagents and products to determine the amounts of each chemical once the reaction is complete.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] In the 1930s–1950s Joachim Hämmerling conducted experiments in which he demonstrated *Acetabularia*'s genetic information is contained in the nucleus.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] This was the first demonstration that genes are encoded by DNA in eukaryotes; earlier studies by Oswald Avery and others had shown that this was true for prokaryotes.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] The name, *Acetabularia*, derives from the Latin word *acetabulum*, a broad, shallow cup used for dipping bread; the upturned cap of *Acetabularia* resembles such a cup.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] For this reason, it is also sometimes called **mermaid's wineglass**.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] In the 19th century, the same designation *Acetabularia* was proposed by George Edward Massee for a genus of fungi (now *Cyphellopus*), but this usage is obsolete and considered invalid as the algal name takes precedence.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] Each *Acetabularia* cell is composed of three segments: the "foot" or basal segment which contains the nucleus, the "stalk", and the "cap".
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] Hämmerling exchanged caps between individuals from two species, *A. mediterranea* and *A. crenulata*.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] *A. mediterranea* has a smooth, disc-shaped cap, while *A. crenulata* has a branched, flower-like cap.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] After the exchange, each transplanted cap gradually changed from its original form to the form typical for the species of the base it was now attached to.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] This showed that the nucleus controlled the form of the cap.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] In another experiment, Hämmerling inserted a nucleus from one species of *Acetabularia* into an intact *Acetabularia* of a different species.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] The *Acetabularia* then produced a hybrid cap with characteristics of both species.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] This showed that both nuclei influenced the form of the cap.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] Hammerling's results showed that the nucleus of a cell contains the genetic information that directs cellular development.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] Although a single cell, *Acetabularia* exhibits a remarkably complex shape and has therefore long been a model organism for studying gene expression and morphogenesis.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] It seems to transport messenger RNA molecules (in an inactive riboprotein form) from the nucleus to its apical tips, where they are translated into proteins.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] These molecules may be activated by proteolysis of their protein carrier molecules, but this has not been verified as yet.
[src:cell-wall/acetabularia] In addition to its gradient in specific mRNA molecules, *Acetabularia* exhibits concentration gradients in several types of molecules, such as ascorbic acid.
[src:cell-wall/achlya] The genus was first circumscribed in Nova Acta Phys.-Med.
[src:cell-wall/achlya] Cur. vol.11 on page 514 in 1823 by Christian Gottfried Daniel Nees von Esenbeck.
[src:cell-wall/achlya] The genus name of *Achlya* is named after Achlys, who in the Hesiodic *Shield of Heracles*, is one of the figures depicted on Heracles' shield, perhaps representing the personification of sorrow.
[src:cell-wall/achlya] Several *Achyla* spp. are pathogens of rice seedlings.
[src:cell-wall/acid] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:cell-wall/acid] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:cell-wall/acid] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:cell-wall/acid] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:cell-wall/acid] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:cell-wall/acid] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:cell-wall/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:cell-wall/acid] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:cell-wall/acid] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:cell-wall/acid] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:cell-wall/acid] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:cell-wall/acid] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:cell-wall/acid] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:cell-wall/acid] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:cell-wall/acid] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:cell-wall/acid] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:cell-wall/acid] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:cell-wall/acid] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:cell-wall/acid] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:cell-wall/acid] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:cell-wall/acid] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:cell-wall/acid] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:cell-wall/acid] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:cell-wall/acid] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:cell-wall/acid] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:cell-wall/acid] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:cell-wall/acid] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:cell-wall/acid] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:cell-wall/acid] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:cell-wall/acid] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:cell-wall/acid] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:cell-wall/acid] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:cell-wall/acid] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:cell-wall/acid] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:cell-wall/acid] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:cell-wall/acid] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:cell-wall/acid] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:cell-wall/acid] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:cell-wall/acid] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:cell-wall/acid] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:cell-wall/acid] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:cell-wall/acid] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:cell-wall/acid] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:cell-wall/acid] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:cell-wall/acid] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:cell-wall/acid] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:cell-wall/acid] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:cell-wall/acid] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:cell-wall/acid] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:cell-wall/acid] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:cell-wall/acid] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:cell-wall/acid] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:cell-wall/acid] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:cell-wall/acid] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:cell-wall/acid] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:cell-wall/acid] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] A **cell wall** is a structural layer that surrounds some cell types, found immediately outside the cell membrane.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] It can be tough, flexible, and sometimes rigid.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Primarily, it provides the cell with structural support, shape, protection, and functions as a selective barrier.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Another vital role of the cell wall is to help the cell withstand osmotic pressure and mechanical stress.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Cell walls are found in most prokaryotes, with the exception of mollicute bacteria.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Among the eukaryotes, cells walls are prevalent in fungi, algae and plants but absent from animals and many other taxa.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The composition of cell walls varies across taxonomic groups, species, cell type, and the cell cycle.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] In land plants, the primary cell wall comprises polysaccharides like cellulose, hemicelluloses, and pectin.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Often, other polymers such as lignin, suberin or cutin are anchored to or embedded in plant cell walls.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Algae exhibit cell walls composed of glycoproteins and polysaccharides, such as carrageenan and agar, distinct from those in land plants.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Bacterial cell walls contain peptidoglycan, while archaeal cell walls vary in composition, potentially consisting of glycoprotein S-layers, pseudopeptidoglycan, or polysaccharides.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Fungi possess cell walls constructed from the polymer chitin, specifically N-acetylglucosamine.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Diatoms have a unique cell wall composed of biogenic silica.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] A plant cell wall was first observed and named (simply as a "wall") by Robert Hooke in 1665.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] However, "the dead excrusion product of the living protoplast" was forgotten, for almost three centuries, being the subject of scientific interest mainly as a resource for industrial processing or in relation to animal or human health.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Link proved that cells had independent cell walls.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Before, it had been thought that cells shared walls and that fluid passed between them this way.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The mode of formation of the cell wall was controversial in the 19th century.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Hugo von Mohl (1853, 1858) advocated the idea that the cell wall grows by apposition.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Carl Nägeli (1858, 1862, 1863) believed that the growth of the wall in thickness and in area was due to a process termed intussusception.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Each theory was improved in the following decades: the apposition (or lamination) theory by Eduard Strasburger (1882, 1889), and the intussusception theory by Julius Wiesner (1886).
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] In 1930, Ernst Münch coined the term *apoplast* in order to separate the "living" symplast from the "dead" plant region, the latter of which included the cell wall.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] By the 1980s, some authors suggested replacing the term "cell wall", particularly as it was used for plants, with the more precise term "extracellular matrix", as used for animal cells, but others preferred the older term.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Cell walls serve similar purposes in those organisms that possess them.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] They may give cells rigidity and strength, offering protection against mechanical stress.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The chemical composition and mechanical properties of the cell wall are linked with plant cell growth and morphogenesis.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] In multicellular organisms, they permit the organism to build and hold a definite shape.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Cell walls also limit the entry of large molecules that may be toxic to the cell.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] They further permit the creation of stable osmotic environments by preventing osmotic lysis and helping to retain water.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Their composition, properties, and form may change during the cell cycle and depend on growth conditions.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] In most cells, the cell wall is flexible, meaning that it will bend rather than holding a fixed shape, but has considerable tensile strength.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The apparent rigidity of primary plant tissues is enabled by cell walls, but is not due to the walls' stiffness.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Hydraulic turgor pressure creates this rigidity, along with the wall structure.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The flexibility of the cell walls is seen when plants wilt, so that the stems and leaves begin to droop, or in seaweeds that bend in water currents.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The apparent rigidity of the cell wall thus results from inflation of the cell contained within.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] This inflation is a result of the passive uptake of water.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Cell walls evolved independently in many groups.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The photosynthetic eukaryotes (plants and algae) have cellulose cell walls, where the cell wall is closely related to the evolution of multicellularity, terrestrialization and vascularization.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The CesA cellulose synthase evolved in *Cyanobacteria* and was part of Archaeplastida since endosymbiosis; secondary endosymbiosis events transferred it (with the arabinogalactan proteins) further into brown algae and oomycetes.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Plants later evolved various genes from CesA, including the Csl (cellulose synthase-like) family of proteins and additional Ces proteins.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Combined with the various glycosyltransferases (GT), they enable more complex chemical structures to be built.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Fungi use a chitin-glucan-protein cell wall.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] They share the 1,3-β-glucan synthesis pathway with plants, using homologous GT48 family 1,3-Beta-glucan synthases to perform the task, suggesting that such an enzyme is very ancient within the eukaryotes.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Their glycoproteins are rich in mannose.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The cell wall might have evolved to deter viral infections.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Proteins embedded in cell walls are variable, contained in tandem repeats subject to homologous recombination.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] An alternative scenario is that fungi started with a chitin-based cell wall and later acquired the GT-48 enzymes for the 1,3-β-glucans via horizontal gene transfer.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The pathway leading to 1,6-β-glucan synthesis is not sufficiently known in either case.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The walls of plant cells must have sufficient tensile strength to withstand internal osmotic pressures of several times atmospheric pressure that result from the difference in solute concentration between the cell interior and external solutions.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Plant cell walls vary from 0.1 to several μm in thickness.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] In plants, a **secondary cell wall** is a thicker additional layer of cellulose which increases wall rigidity.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Additional layers may be formed by lignin in xylem cell walls, or suberin in cork cell walls.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] These compounds are rigid and waterproof, making the secondary wall stiff.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Both wood and bark cells of trees have secondary walls.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Other parts of plants such as the leaf stalk may acquire similar reinforcement to resist the strain of physical forces.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The **primary cell wall** of most plant cells is freely permeable to small molecules including small proteins, with size exclusion estimated to be 30–60 kDa.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The pH is an important abiotic factor governing the transport of molecules through cell walls.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] In the primary (growing) plant cell wall, the major carbohydrates are cellulose, hemicellulose and pectin.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The cellulose microfibrils are linked via hemicellulosic tethers to form the cellulose-hemicellulose network, which is embedded in the pectin matrix.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The most common hemicellulose in the primary cell wall is xyloglucan.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] In grass cell walls, xyloglucan and pectin are reduced in abundance and partially replaced by glucuronoarabinoxylan, another type of hemicellulose.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Primary cell walls characteristically extend (grow) by a mechanism called acid growth, mediated by expansins, extracellular proteins activated by acidic conditions that modify the hydrogen bonds between pectin and cellulose.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] This functions to increase cell wall extensibility.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The outer part of the primary cell wall of the plant epidermis is usually impregnated with cutin and wax, forming a permeability barrier known as the plant cuticle.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Secondary cell walls contain a wide range of additional compounds that modify their mechanical properties and permeability.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Additionally, structural proteins (1-5%) are found in most plant cell walls; they are classified as hydroxyproline-rich glycoproteins (HRGP), arabinogalactan proteins (AGP), glycine-rich proteins (GRPs), and proline-rich proteins (PRPs).
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Each class of glycoprotein is defined by a characteristic, highly repetitive protein sequence.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Most are glycosylated, contain hydroxyproline (Hyp) and become cross-linked in the cell wall.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] These proteins are often concentrated in specialized cells and in cell corners.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Cell walls of the epidermis may contain cutin.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The Casparian strip in the endodermis roots and cork cells of plant bark contain suberin.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Both cutin and suberin are polyesters that function as permeability barriers to the movement of water.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The relative composition of carbohydrates, secondary compounds and proteins varies between plants and between the cell type and age.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Plant cells walls also contain numerous enzymes, such as hydrolases, esterases, peroxidases, and transglycosylases, that cut, trim and cross-link wall polymers.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Secondary walls - especially in grasses - may also contain microscopic silica crystals, which may strengthen the wall and protect it from herbivores.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Cell walls in some plant tissues also function as storage deposits for carbohydrates that can be broken down and resorbed to supply the metabolic and growth needs of the plant.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] For example, endosperm cell walls in the seeds of cereal grasses, nasturtium and other species, are rich in glucans and other polysaccharides that are readily digested by enzymes during seed germination to form simple sugars that nourish the growing embryo.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The middle lamella is laid down first, formed from the cell plate during cytokinesis, and the primary cell wall is then deposited inside the middle lamella.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The actual structure of the cell wall is not clearly defined and several models exist - the covalently linked cross model, the tether model, the diffuse layer model and the stratified layer model.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] However, the primary cell wall, can be defined as composed of cellulose microfibrils aligned at all angles.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Cellulose microfibrils are produced at the plasma membrane by the cellulose synthase complex, which is proposed to be made of a hexameric rosette that contains three cellulose synthase catalytic subunits for each of the six units.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Microfibrils are held together by hydrogen bonds to provide a high tensile strength.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The cells are held together and share the gelatinous membrane (the middle lamella), which contains magnesium and calcium pectates (salts of pectic acid).
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Cells interact though plasmodesmata, which are inter-connecting channels of cytoplasm that connect to the protoplasts of adjacent cells across the cell wall.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] In some plants and cell types, after a maximum size or point in development has been reached, a *secondary wall* is constructed between the plasma membrane and primary wall.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Unlike the primary wall, the cellulose microfibrils are aligned parallel in layers, the orientation changing slightly with each additional layer so that the structure becomes helicoidal.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Cells with secondary cell walls can be rigid, as in the gritty sclereid cells in pear and quince fruit.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Cell to cell communication is possible through pits in the secondary cell wall that allow plasmodesmata to connect cells through the secondary cell walls.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] There are several groups of organisms that have been called "fungi".
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Some of these groups (Oomycete and Myxogastria) have been transferred out of the Kingdom Fungi, in part because of fundamental biochemical differences in the composition of the cell wall.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Most true fungi have a cell wall consisting largely of chitin and other polysaccharides.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] True fungi do not have cellulose in their cell walls.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] In fungi, the cell wall is the outer-most layer, external to the plasma membrane.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Algal cell walls contain either polysaccharides (such as cellulose (a glucan)) or a variety of glycoproteins (Volvocales) or both.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The inclusion of additional polysaccharides in algal cells walls is used as a feature for algal taxonomy.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Other compounds that may accumulate in algal cell walls include sporopollenin and calcium ions.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The group of algae known as the diatoms synthesize their cell walls (also known as frustules or valves) from silicic acid.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Significantly, relative to the organic cell walls produced by other groups, silica frustules require less energy to synthesize (approximately 8%), potentially a major saving on the overall cell energy budget and possibly an explanation for higher growth rates in diatoms.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] In brown algae, phlorotannins may be a constituent of the cell walls.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The group Oomycetes, also known as water molds, are saprotrophic plant pathogens like fungi.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Until recently they were widely believed to be fungi, but structural and molecular evidence has led to their reclassification as heterokonts, related to autotrophic brown algae and diatoms.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Unlike fungi, oomycetes typically possess cell walls of cellulose and glucans rather than chitin, although some genera (such as *Achlya* and *Saprolegnia*) do have chitin in their walls.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The fraction of cellulose in the walls is no more than 4 to 20%, far less than the fraction of glucans.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Oomycete cell walls also contain the amino acid hydroxyproline, which is not found in fungal cell walls.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The dictyostelids are another group formerly classified among the fungi.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] They are slime molds that feed as unicellular amoebae, but aggregate into a reproductive stalk and sporangium under certain conditions.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Cells of the reproductive stalk, as well as the spores formed at the apex, possess a cellulose wall.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The spore wall has three layers, the middle one composed primarily of cellulose, while the innermost is sensitive to cellulase and pronase.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Around the outside of the cell membrane is the bacterial cell wall.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Bacterial cell walls are made of peptidoglycan (also called murein), which is made from polysaccharide chains cross-linked by D-peptides (unusual peptides containing D-amino acids).
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Bacterial cell walls are different from the cell walls of plants and fungi which are made of cellulose and chitin, respectively.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The cell wall of bacteria is also distinct from that of Archaea, which do not contain peptidoglycan.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The cell wall is essential to the survival of many bacteria, although L-form bacteria can be produced in the laboratory that lack a cell wall.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The antibiotic penicillin is able to kill bacteria by preventing the cross-linking of peptidoglycan and this causes the cell wall to weaken and lyse.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The lysozyme enzyme can also damage bacterial cell walls.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] There are broadly speaking two different types of cell wall in bacteria, called gram-positive and gram-negative.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The names originate from the reaction of cells to the Gram stain, a test long-employed for the classification of bacterial species.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Gram-positive bacteria possess a thick cell wall containing many layers of peptidoglycan and teichoic acids.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Gram-negative bacteria have a relatively thin cell wall consisting of a few layers of peptidoglycan surrounded by a second lipid membrane containing lipopolysaccharides and lipoproteins.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Most bacteria have the gram-negative cell wall and only the Bacillota and Actinomycetota (previously known as the low G+C and high G+C gram-positive bacteria, respectively) have the alternative gram-positive arrangement.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] These differences in structure produce differences in antibiotic susceptibility.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The beta-lactam antibiotics (e.g. penicillin, cephalosporin) only work against gram-negative pathogens, such as *Haemophilus influenzae* or *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Although not truly unique, the cell walls of Archaea are unusual.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Whereas peptidoglycan is a standard component of all bacterial cell walls, all archaeal cell walls lack peptidoglycan, though some methanogens have a cell wall made of a similar polymer called pseudopeptidoglycan.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] There are four types of cell wall currently known among the Archaea.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] One type of archaeal cell wall is that composed of pseudopeptidoglycan (also called pseudomurein).
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] This type of wall is found in some methanogens, such as *Methanobacterium* and *Methanothermus*.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] While the overall structure of archaeal *pseudo*peptidoglycan superficially resembles that of bacterial peptidoglycan, there are a number of significant chemical differences.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Like the peptidoglycan found in bacterial cell walls, pseudopeptidoglycan consists of polymer chains of glycan cross-linked by short peptide connections.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] However, unlike peptidoglycan, the sugar N-acetylmuramic acid is replaced by N-acetyltalosaminuronic acid, and the two sugars are bonded with a *β*,1-3 glycosidic linkage instead of *β*,1-4.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Additionally, the cross-linking peptides are L-amino acids rather than D-amino acids as they are in bacteria.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] A second type of archaeal cell wall is found in *Methanosarcina* and *Halococcus*.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] This type of cell wall is composed entirely of a thick layer of polysaccharides, which may be sulfated in the case of *Halococcus*.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Structure in this type of wall is complex and not fully investigated.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] A third type of wall among the Archaea consists of glycoprotein, and occurs in the hyperthermophiles, *Halobacterium*, and some methanogens.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] In *Halobacterium*, the proteins in the wall have a high content of acidic amino acids, giving the wall an overall negative charge.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] The result is an unstable structure that is stabilized by the presence of large quantities of positive sodium ions that neutralize the charge.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Consequently, *Halobacterium* thrives only under conditions with high salinity.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] In other Archaea, such as *Methanomicrobium* and *Desulfurococcus*, the wall may be composed only of surface-layer proteins, known as an *S-layer*.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] S-layers are common in bacteria, where they serve as either the sole cell-wall component or an outer layer in conjunction with polysaccharides.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Most Archaea are Gram-negative, though at least one Gram-positive member is known.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Many protists and bacteria produce other cell surface structures apart from cell walls, external (extracellular matrix) or internal.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Many algae have a sheath or envelope of mucilage outside the cell made of exopolysaccharides.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Diatoms build a frustule from silica extracted from the surrounding water; radiolarians, foraminiferans, testate amoebae and silicoflagellates also produce a skeleton from minerals, called test in some groups.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Many green algae, such as *Halimeda* and the Dasycladales, and some red algae, the Corallinales, encase their cells in a secreted skeleton of calcium carbonate.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] In each case, the wall is rigid and essentially inorganic.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Some golden algae, ciliates and choanoflagellates produces a shell-like protective outer covering called lorica.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Some dinoflagellates have a theca of cellulose plates, and coccolithophorids have coccoliths.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] An extracellular matrix (ECM) is also present in metazoans.
[src:cell-wall/cell-wall] Its composition varies between cells, but collagens are the most abundant protein in the ECM.
